How this structure works
1. Year‑based folders
Each year gets its own folder:
• 	Keeps the archive clean
• 	Makes governance actions easy to browse
• 	Mirrors how standards bodies maintain long‑term records
2. Date‑stamped filenames
Every announcement uses the format:

YYYY-MM-Title.md
This ensures:
• 	Chronological sorting
• 	Predictable naming
• 	Zero ambiguity when multiple announcements occur in the same month
3. Clear, descriptive titles
Each filename includes:
• 	The standard (SCS‑1)
• 	The action (Drafting‑Open, Draft‑Published, Final‑Release)
• 	The version (v1.1, v1.2, etc.)
This makes the archive self‑documenting.
4. index.md
This file provides:
• 	A chronological list of all announcements
• 	Links to each file
• 	A short description of each governance action
It becomes the “table of contents” for the entire announcements archive.

Why this structure is correct
This mirrors the archival practices of:
• 	W3C (Status of This Document + dated announcements)
• 	ISO (dated notices in year‑based folders)
• 	NIST (SP 800 series notices archived by year)
It ensures SCS‑1 remains:
• 	Professional
• 	Navigable
• 	Auditable
• 	Future‑proof
